{{for|the Australian architect|Samuel Shenton (architect)}}
{{refimprove|date=November 2017}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}
{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}

'''Samuel Shenton''' (March 1903 – 2 March 1971) was the founder in 1956 of the ''Flat Earth Society'', based in [[Dover, England]]. He lectured tirelessly on this to youth clubs, political and student groups and during the [[Space Race]] in the 1960s he was frequently seen on television and in newspapers promoting his views. He was well known for his promotion of the theory, but had a reputation as being a primary school dropout.

==Life==
Samuel Shenton was a signwriter, who lived with his wife Lillian in a ginger-brick terrace in suburban Dover. He was son of an army sergeant major, born in [[Great Yarmouth]], and by the 1920s claimed to have invented an airship that would rise into the atmosphere and remain stationary until the earth spun westwards at {{convert|1000|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} to the desired destination at the same latitude. Shenton could not understand why someone had not previously thought of this idea until he discovered, in the reading room of the [[British Library]] at [[Bloomsbury]] that [[Charles Isaac Stevens|Archbishop Stevens]], a friend of Lady Blount, the founder of the [[Universal Zetetic Society]], had suggested an aircraft design similar to his own. When he discovered [[Samuel Rowbotham|Parallax]]'s ''Zetetic Astronomy'' he was an instant convert. "What the authorities were concealing, Shenton decided, was the 'fact' that the earth was flat".<ref>{{harvnb|Garwood|2007|pp=220–222}}</ref>.

He discovered this theory in primary school, and had a reputation in his community as being an primary school drop out.

Shenton soon constructed a cosmology, based partly on his interpretation of [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]], that the earth was a flat disk centred on the [[North Pole]] with the zetetic notion of the [[South Pole]] being an impenetrable wall of ice, that marked the edge of the pit that is the earth in the endless flat plane forming the universe. The sun cast a narrow beam like a flashlight moving over a table as it traced flat circles that varied over the 365-day cycles. The sun was {{convert|32|mi}} in diameter {{convert|3000|mi}} above the earth and the moon also 32 miles in diameter but only {{convert|2550|mi}} above the earth.

In 1956 he founded the Flat Earth Society as a direct descendant of the Universal Zetetic Society but with a less religious emphasis, found a president in William Mills, a relative of one of Lady Blount's followers and held its inaugural meeting in November at Mills' home in London, with Shenton as secretary. One of the attendees, attending out of curiosity, was the ''[[The Sky at Night|Sky at Night]]'' astronomer [[Patrick Moore]] who recounted his experience in his book ''Can you speak Venusian?''. Shenton claimed that [[George Bernard Shaw]] attended one meeting, declaring the presentation was "very persuasive".<ref name="Gilmore 1967" /> Despite his contrary ideas, Shenton was elected a fellow of both the [[Royal Astronomical Society|Royal Astronomical]] and [[Royal Geographical Society|Royal Geographical]] Societies.<ref name="Gilmore 1967">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17484882/the_cincinnati_enquirer|title=So now we know: The Earth is not only flat—it's motionless, too|last=Gilmore|first=Eddy|date=26 March 1967|work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|access-date=15 February 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|page=26-I|subscription=y|via=Newspapers.com}}  {{free access}} Readable clippings in four parts: [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17484925/the_cincinnati_enquirer/ 1] • 
[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17484950/the_cincinnati_enquirer/ 2] • 
[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17484958/the_cincinnati_enquirer/ 3] • [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17484965/the_cincinnati_enquirer/ 4]</ref>

Despite the launch in October 1957 of [[Sputnik]], the world's first artificial satellite, Shenton proved a popular speaker to small groups, enjoying particularly talking to children, never declining an invitation. [[File:SF10084a.jpg|thumb|Samuel Shenton lecturing at the Science Fiction Society, UCL, in 1966.]] He claimed that satellites simply circled over a flat disc-world: "Would sailing round the [[Isle of Wight]] prove that it were spherical?", he demanded. As manned space flight started in 1961, Shenton began to attract international media attention with his denials, telling the ''[[Coshocton Tribune]]'' on 10 May that the astronauts could never travel into orbit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17487617/the_tribune/|title=Orbiting globe impossible, Flat Earth Society claims|last=Musel|first=Robert|date=10 May 1961|work=The Tribune|access-date=15 February 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|agency=United Press International|location=Coshocton, Ohio|page=12|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>

When [[John Glenn]] orbited the world, he was sent an IFERS membership with the message "Ok Wise Guy" added to it.<ref>
{{cite web|author=John Glenn|title=Friendship 7, 20 Years Later Random Remembrances|url=http://library.osu.edu/sites/archives/glenn/legacy/20year.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904153343/http://library.osu.edu/sites/archives/glenn/legacy/20year.htm|archivedate=4 Sep 2006}}
</ref> Shenton continued to lecture largely at his own expense but he suffered two strokes in 1963 probably as a result of his exertions.{{According to whom|date=February 2018|probably as a result of his exertions.}} In January 1964 the ''[[New York Times]]'' carried a piece about the IFERS.{{Relevance inline|sentence|date=February 2018}}  During a parliamentary debate, [[Enoch Powell]] likened his opponents to "flat-earthers" and [[Harold Wilson]] reportedly slung back the insult in turn. Shenton was outraged and wrote letters of complaint.

The [[Gemini 4]] mission marked a change of pace for his campaign and he was to receive letters from across the world for the next few years.<ref name="Gilmore 1967" /> In 1966 he produced a pamphlet, ''The Plane Truth'', which included a circular informing members "that modern astronomy and space flight were insults to God and divine punishment for humankind's arrogance was a mere matter of time". But the [[Lunar Orbiter program]] led to a sharp decline in membership. "Visual images, whether they were globes, photographs or television pictures, were clearly critical to how people perceived the earth's shape .. and pre-school children could know that it was round even if they had no grasp of the words 'mathematics', 'geography', 'astronomy' and 'science'".<ref>{{harvnb|Garwood|2007|pp=234–238}}</ref>

By 1968, his health had deteriorated further and his signwriting business had collapsed although the media attention continued. But he stuck to his principles of 'zetetic enquiry' in which only personally acquired facts were permissible. In January 1969, IFERS had dropped to 100 members worldwide.<ref name="Coleman 1969">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17488536/the_guardian/|title=The league of lost causes–4: Globites are not convinced|last=Coleman|first=Terry|date=2 January 1969|work=The Guardian|location=London, England|access-date=15 February 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|page=7|subscription=y|via=Newspapers.com}} {{free access}} Readable clippings in three parts: [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17488548/the_guardian/ 1] • 
[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17488571/the_guardian/ 2] • 
[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17488578/the_guardian/ 3]</ref> But as his organization was dying, he found the successor he had been looking for: [[Ellis Hillman]], a lecturer and member of the [[Greater London Council]], agreed to be president of the IFERS, with the encouragement of [[Patrick Moore]]. Lillian Shenton was suspicious of his motives (he was developing a post-graduate course on the development of ideas about the shape of the earth) and in the event he did little for the society. Eighteen months later, Shenton had died.

