{{Earthquakes}}
A '''volcano tectonic earthquake''' is an [[earthquake]] induced by the movement (injection or withdrawal) of [[magma]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://jclahr.com/alaska/aeic/redoubt/JVGR1994.pdf |first=J. C. |last=Lahr |first2=B. A. |last2=Chouet |first3=C. D. |last3=Stephens |first4=J. A. |last4=Power |first5=R. A. |last5=Page |year=1994 |title=Earthquake classification, location, and error analysis in a volcanic environment: implications for the magmatic system of the 1989–1990 eruptions at Redoubt Volcano, Alaska |journal=Journal of Volcanology and Geothermal Research |volume=62 |issue=1–4 |pages=137–151 |doi=10.1016/0377-0273(94)90031-0 |bibcode = 1994JVGR...62..137L }}</ref> The movement results in pressure changes in the rock around where the magma has experienced stress. At some point, the rock may break or move. The earthquakes may also be related to [[dike (geology)|dike]] [[intrusion]] and may occur as [[earthquake swarm]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://geology.geoscienceworld.org/cgi/content/abstract/34/6/457 |last=Roman |first=D. C. |last2=Cashman |first2=K. V. |authorlink2=Katharine Cashman|year=2006 |title=The origin of volcano-tectonic earthquake swarms |journal=[[Geology (journal)|Geology]] |volume=34 |issue=6 |pages=457–460 |doi=10.1130/G22269.1 |bibcode = 2006Geo....34..457R }}</ref> An example is the [[2007–2008 Nazko earthquakes|2007–2008 Nazko earthquake swarm]] in central [[British Columbia]], Canada.

Other types of seismic activity related to [[volcanoes]] and their eruptions are long period [[seismic wave]]s, which are from sudden sporadic movement of magma, which is blocked from moving due to a blockage.  Another is a [[harmonic tremor]], which is steady movement of magma, deep in the [[mantle (geology)|mantle]].

